evidence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">General Response</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We believe that the ‘power to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">disapply</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> legislation no longer of practical use’ should be extended to include ‘no longer of practical use or justifiable environmental benefit’. This addition would ensure that any legislation which would be considered under Clause 51 would not be in contradiction to furthering the UK’s environmental commitments. It is also considered that the terms ‘practical use’ and ‘justifiable environmental benefit’ should be defined, or that each application made under Clause 51 be subject to an Impact Assessment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Further to the above, it would also be practical to define the qualification criteria of Clause 58 (1) ‘have regard to promoting economic growth’. It must be ensured that while promoting economic growth there is not a detrimental effect on any other aspects, and that any impact made is distributed evenly. Again, an Impact Assessment may be able to assess the necessary information in these instances.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Clause 54 (1) b) outlines that a Minster must consult with ‘such persons as the Minster considers appropriate’ when making on order under Clause 51. In order to ensure that this Clause would be used effectively we propose an addition to the wording to include ‘including, but not limited to, any regulating body affected by the legislation in question’. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>